Path: docs/image-deletion-examples.md
 1	# Product Image Deletion API Examples
 2	
 3	## Overview
 4	The image deletion endpoint allows you to delete specific images from a product using the image URL. This performs both database soft-delete and Cloudinary cleanup.
 5	
 6	## Endpoint Details
 7	
 8	### Delete Product Image
 9	```
 10	DELETE /api/products/:productId/images
 11	```
 12	
 13	**Request Body Required:** Image URL to delete
 14	
 15	## Usage Examples
 16	
 17	### 1. Basic Image Deletion
 18	
 19	**Request:**
 20	```http
 21	DELETE /api/products/220/images
 22	Authorization: Bearer your-jwt-token
 23	Content-Type: application/json
 24	
 25	{
 26	 "imageUrl": "https://res.cloudinary.com/dbgfyigqr/image/upload/v1234567890/products/product_220_1703123456789_0.jpg"
 27	}
...
 119	
 120	- **Soft Delete**: Images are marked as deleted, not permanently removed
 121	- **Ownership Check**: Ensures image belongs to the specified product
 122	- **Graceful Degradation**: Database operation succeeds even if Cloudinary deletion fails
 123	- **Authentication**: Requires valid JWT token
 124	- **Validation**: Validates all parameters before processing
 125	
 126	### Cloudinary Integration:
 127	
 128	The endpoint automatically:
 129	- Extracts the public ID from the Cloudinary URL
 130	- Calls Cloudinary's deletion API
 131	- Reports whether Cloudinary deletion was successful
 132	- Continues operation even if Cloudinary deletion fails
 133	
 134	## Testing with Postman/Thunder Client
 135	
 136	### Step 1: Get Product with Images
 137	```
 138	GET http://localhost:3000/api/products/220
 139	Authorization: Bearer your-jwt-token
 140	```
...
 154	```
 155	
 156	### Step 4: Verify Deletion
 157	```
 158	GET http://localhost:3000/api/products/220
 159	Authorization: Bearer your-jwt-token
 160	```
 161	
 162	The deleted image should no longer appear in the images array.
 163	
 164	## Frontend Integration Example
 165	
 166	```javascript
 167	// Get product images
 168	const product = await fetch('/api/products/220').then(r => r.json());
 169	const imageToDelete = product.data.images[0]; // First image URL
 170	
 171	// Delete the image
 172	const deleteResult = await fetch('/api/products/220/images', {
 173	 method: 'DELETE',
 174	 headers: {
 175	 'Authorization': 'Bearer your-jwt-token',
 176	 'Content-Type': 'application/json'
 177	 },
 178	 body: JSON.stringify({
 179	 imageUrl: imageToDelete
 180	 })
 181	});
